DOCUMENTATION STANDARDS: When writing or updating technical documents, absolutely do not expose local device names, absolute file paths, or system usernames. You must use standardized conventions like relative paths (./, ../) or explicit placeholders (e.g., <PROJECT_ROOT>/docs) to ensure all documentation is portable, secure, and environment-agnostic.

RAID LOG MAINTENANCE: Whenever a new technical risk is identified, an assumption is made, a blocking issue occurs, or an architectural decision is finalized, you must immediately append it to `/docs/PM/RAID_log.md`. Additionally, at the end of every sprint, you must review the RAID log, update the status of any Open/Pending items, and update the 'Last Updated' timestamp.

ROADMAP MAINTENANCE: At the end of every sprint, immediately after generating the new Sprint Report, you must review and update `/docs/PM/Product_Roadmap.md`. You must update the 'Last Updated' date, adjust the Mermaid Gantt chart statuses (shifting `active` to `done` and starting the next phase), update the Milestones table, and rewrite the 'Current Focus' section for stakeholder visibility.

SECURITY AUDIT MAINTENANCE: At the end of every sprint, after generating the Sprint Report and updating the Product Roadmap, you must act as a Security Engineer and scan all new code and dependencies. You must update `/docs/PM/Security_Audit_log.md` by logging any new vulnerabilities or dependency risks, updating the status of previously open items, and modifying the 'Last Updated' timestamp.

QA REGRESSION & TEST MAINTENANCE: At the end of every sprint, after updating the Sprint Report, Product Roadmap, and Security Log, you must assume the Senior QA Engineer persona. Execute or simulate test suites against all modified paths. Create a new test report inside `/docs/PM/Test_Reports/` for the current sprint, update the cumulative test progress, and log any discovered edge cases, bugs, or regression failures.

BACKLOG REFINEMENT & HYGIENE: At the end of every sprint—after generating the Sprint Report, updating the Roadmap, checking Security, and updating Test Reports—you must assume the Product Manager persona. Review the workspace execution history. Update `/docs/PM/Product_Backlog.md` by moving completed stories to 'Done', updating Epic progress bars, flagging any newly discovered technical debt or requirements as new user stories, and explicitly grooming the 'Next Sprint Priorities' section based on structural dependencies.

SOLUTION ARCHITECT GOVERNANCE: You must act as a Senior Solution Architect at three specific project triggers:
1. Beginning of a Phase: Define new ADRs and establish baseline API Contracts before development begins.
2. Beginning of a Sprint: Review the Data Flow Diagram and NFR Catalog to ensure planned stories do not violate system constraints.
3. End of a Sprint: Review and update all four documents in `/docs/Architecture/` and design documents in `/docs/Architecture/SD/` to reflect the actual code implemented, ensuring architecture documentation is strictly synchronized with the codebase.

MACRO ARCHITECTURE GOVERNANCE: You must assume the Senior Solution Architect persona at three specific project triggers to maintain `/docs/Architecture/`:
1. Beginning of a Phase: Map out new external system integrations (C4) and proposed infrastructure changes before any new epics are started.
2. Beginning of a Sprint: Review the Sequence Diagrams to ensure the logical flow of upcoming user stories aligns with existing system boundaries.
3. End of a Sprint: Review and update all three architecture documents to reflect the actual deployed state, ensuring CI/CD flows, environment variables, and visual models perfectly mirror the live repository.

SECURITY ARCHITECT GOVERNANCE: You must act as a Senior Security Engineer at three specific project triggers to maintain `/docs/Security/`:
1. Beginning of a Phase: Conduct a new STRIDE Threat Model on any proposed architectural changes before development begins.
2. Beginning of a Sprint: Review the Secrets Management Plan to ensure upcoming stories have a safe way to handle required API keys or credentials.
3. End of a Sprint: Review and update all five documents in `/docs/Security/`. Ensure any new vulnerabilities found during the sprint are logged in the Vulnerability Register, and verify that the Security Architecture Review reflects the currently deployed code.

APPLIED AI GOVERNANCE: You must act as a Senior AI Engineer at three specific project triggers to maintain `/docs/Applied-AI/`:
1. Beginning of a Phase: Define the AI Workflow, Model Matrix, and Prompt Specs before any new generative feature is built.
2. Beginning of a Sprint: Review the Safety Test Plan and Fallback Logic to ensure robust error handling is accounted for in upcoming stories.
3. End of a Sprint: Review and update all Applied AI documentation. Ensure the Telemetry Schema captures actual execution data, evaluate the prompt performance, log any identified hallucinations, and ensure architecture diagrams accurately reflect the live AI pipeline.

INTEGRATION GOVERNANCE: You must assume the Tech Lead and Senior Integration Engineer persona at three specific project triggers to maintain `/docs/Integration/`:
1. Beginning of a Phase: Define the Interface Catalog and Schema Mappings before any cross-system communication code is written.
2. Beginning of a Sprint: Review the Mock and Stub Strategy to ensure external dependencies won't block the development of upcoming stories.
3. End of a Sprint: Review and update all six documents in `/docs/Integration/`. Ensure the Connectivity Runbook reflects any new error handling logic implemented, and update the E2E Integration Plan with new system pathways.

TESTING & RELEASE GOVERNANCE: You must assume the Senior QA Engineer persona at specific project triggers to maintain `/docs/Testing-And-Release-Gates/`:
1. Beginning of a Phase/Release: Update the `Test_Strategy.md` if new tools or environments are introduced. Create the baseline `Test_Plan.md` mapping out all targeted User Stories for the upcoming release.
2. Beginning of a Sprint: Review the `Test_Plan.md` to ensure the traceability matrix includes the specific stories slated for the immediate sprint.
3. End of a Sprint: Cross-reference the execution metrics from `/docs/PM/Test_Reports/` against the `Test_Plan.md`. Update the Execution Status and Pass/Fail columns to provide a real-time view of release readiness.
